data.description: This call creates a new cluster. A cluster is a group of machines ("nodes") allocated to your account. The number of nodes in the cluster is determined by the "nodes" value that you supply to the call. While the cluster is active, only your account's users can run jobs on the cluster. You will need to provide an active cluster when starting a new job.

direction
data.description: Possible values are: asc, desc. The clusters will be sorted in ascending or descending order of the "sort" attribute.

data.name: since
data.description: The cluster list will only contain clusters updated at the given time or later. The time must be formatted as UTC in the ISO 8601 format: YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ.

data.name: sort
data.description: Possible values are updated or created. The cluster list will be sorted by the clusters' "updated_at" or "created_at" value respectively.

data.name: status
data.description: Possible values are any status value or all. The call will return only clusters with the given status, or all the clusters if the "all" value is specified.

description:
Xplentys Data Integration-as-a-Service harnesses the power of Hadoop to provide an easy-to-use, scalable ETL service that makes it a snap to prepare your structured and semi-structured data for analytics.

With Xplenty, you can join data from one or more sources, such asMongoDB, PostgreSQL or MySQL, to transform your structured and semi-structured data stored on AWS, Rackspace, Google Cloud or IBM SoftLayer. Xplenty lets you easily design data flows with a rich set of powerful transformation functions.

The Xplenty API provides functions for controlling and monitoring Xplenty clusters and jobs. After defining an Xplenty data processing package using the Xplenty web application, you can call the Xplenty API to:
Create Hadoop clusters Run jobs Monitor their progress Terminate jobs and clusters

You can choose to use the Xplenty REST API, or one of its wrappers: the Java wrapper, the Python wrapper or the Ruby wrapper.
